1
00:00:07,132 --> 00:00:09,510
ROSE: What's the emergency?
DOCTOR: It's mauve.

2
00:00:09,593 --> 00:00:10,844
Mauve?

3
00:00:12,971 --> 00:00:15,140
Universally recognised colour for danger.

4
00:00:15,265 --> 00:00:17,226
-What happened to red?
-That's just humans.

5
00:00:17,309 --> 00:00:19,520
By everyone else's standards,
red's camp.

6
00:00:19,603 --> 00:00:22,814
Oh, the misunderstandings.
All those red alerts, all that dancing.

7
00:00:22,940 --> 00:00:26,485
It's got a very basic flight computer
I've hacked in, slaved the Tardis.

8
00:00:26,610 --> 00:00:27,903
Wherever it goes, we go.

9
00:00:27,986 --> 00:00:30,113
-And that's safe, is it?
-Totally.

10
00:00:33,325 --> 00:00:36,453
Okay, reasonably.
Should have said "reasonably” there.

11
00:00:37,496 --> 00:00:40,332
No. No! It's jumping time tracks,
getting away from us.

12
00:00:40,457 --> 00:00:42,751
-What exactly is this thing?
-No idea.

13
00:00:42,834 --> 00:00:44,169
Then why are we chasing it?

14
00:00:44,294 --> 00:00:48,382
It's mauve and dangerous and about
30 seconds from the centre of London.

15
00:00:52,219 --> 00:00:54,471
(DOCTOR WHO THEME MUSIC)

16
00:01:32,676 --> 00:01:35,012
(WHOOSHING)

17
00:01:40,267 --> 00:01:42,436
DOCTOR: Know how long you can
knock around space

18
00:01:42,519 --> 00:01:44,146
without happening
to bump into Earth?

19
00:01:44,229 --> 00:01:46,648
ROSE: Five days.
Or is that when we're out of milk?

20
00:01:46,732 --> 00:01:50,777
Of all the species in all the universe
and it has to come out of a cow.

21
00:01:52,863 --> 00:01:56,366
Must've come down somewhere quite close.
Within a mile anyway.

22
00:01:56,575 --> 00:01:59,828
And it can't have been more than
a few weeks ago. Maybe a month.

23
00:01:59,911 --> 00:02:02,289
A month?
We were right behind it.

24
00:02:02,414 --> 00:02:06,209
It was jumping time tracks all over the place.
We're bound to be a little bit out.

25
00:02:06,293 --> 00:02:08,879
DOCTOR: Do you want to drive?
ROSE: Yeah.

26
00:02:08,962 --> 00:02:11,256
-How much is a little?
-A bit.

27
00:02:11,381 --> 00:02:13,717
-Is that exactly a bit?
-Ish.

28
00:02:14,426 --> 00:02:15,677
What's the plan, then?

29
00:02:15,761 --> 00:02:17,971
You going to do a scan
for alien tech or something?

30
00:02:18,055 --> 00:02:22,225
Rose, it hit the middle of London
with a very loud bang. I'm going to ask.

31
00:02:22,893 --> 00:02:25,270
"Dr John Smith, Ministry of Asteroids."

32
00:02:25,395 --> 00:02:27,314
It's psychic paper, it tells you what...

33
00:02:27,397 --> 00:02:30,233
-Whatever you want it to, I remember.
-Sorry.

34
00:02:30,317 --> 00:02:33,320
Not very "Spock”, is it?
Just asking.

35
00:02:33,987 --> 00:02:35,989
Door, music, people.
What do you think?

36
00:02:36,073 --> 00:02:38,617
I think you should scan for alien tech.

37
00:02:38,742 --> 00:02:41,703
Give me some Spock, for once.
Would it kill you?

38
00:02:41,787 --> 00:02:43,747
You sure about that T-shirt?

39
00:02:45,248 --> 00:02:48,001
Too early to say.
I'm taking it out for a spin.

40
00:02:49,252 --> 00:02:51,171
CHILD: Mummy.

41
00:02:53,298 --> 00:02:55,133
Mummy.

42
00:02:58,512 --> 00:03:01,431
Come on if you're coming.
It won't take a minute.

43
00:03:03,517 --> 00:03:05,769
CHILD: Mummy?

44
00:03:06,478 --> 00:03:08,980
(SUSPENSEFUL INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC)

45
00:03:09,981 --> 00:03:13,610
ROSE: Doctor, there's a kid up there!

46
00:03:20,367 --> 00:03:22,828
(JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING)

47
00:03:39,636 --> 00:03:42,723
# For nobody else

48
00:03:43,014 --> 00:03:45,475
# Gave me the thrill

49
00:03:46,351 --> 00:03:51,064
# When I uphold silence still

50
00:03:51,148 --> 00:03:53,817
# It had to be you

51
00:03:53,900 --> 00:03:56,153
# Wonderful you #

52
00:03:57,654 --> 00:03:59,239
Are you all right up there?

53
00:03:59,322 --> 00:04:01,575
Mummy.

54
00:04:06,538 --> 00:04:09,166
# It had to be you #

55
00:04:19,676 --> 00:04:23,263
Excuse me, could I have
everybody's attention just for a mo?

56
00:04:23,388 --> 00:04:25,682
Be very quick. Hello?

57
00:04:25,766 --> 00:04:29,269
Erm...might seem like a stupid question

58
00:04:29,352 --> 00:04:32,063
but has anything fallen
from the sky recently?

59
00:04:36,860 --> 00:04:38,862
(ALL LAUGHING)

60
00:04:53,585 --> 00:04:54,753
Mummy.

61
00:04:57,047 --> 00:04:58,882
Okay, hang on, don't move.

62
00:05:12,771 --> 00:05:15,065
Sorry, have I said something funny?

63
00:05:15,273 --> 00:05:17,692
It's just there's this thing
that I need to find.

64
00:05:17,776 --> 00:05:20,904
Would have fallen from the sky,
a couple of days ago.

65
00:05:21,238 --> 00:05:23,281
(SIREN WAILING)

66
00:05:23,490 --> 00:05:25,742
Would have landed
quite near here.

67
00:05:28,745 --> 00:05:30,413
With a very loud...

68
00:05:30,580 --> 00:05:33,333
MAN: Quickly as you can,
down to the shelter.

69
00:05:36,336 --> 00:05:37,587
...bang.

70
00:05:42,592 --> 00:05:43,927
CHILD: Mummy.

71
00:05:46,763 --> 00:05:48,098
Balloon.

72
00:05:54,771 --> 00:05:56,606
(ROSE SCREAMING)

73
00:06:01,278 --> 00:06:02,487
Doctor!

74
00:06:07,367 --> 00:06:08,785
Doctor!

75
00:06:10,495 --> 00:06:12,330
Doctor!

76
00:06:21,214 --> 00:06:24,050
Okay. Maybe not this T-shirt.

77
00:06:31,516 --> 00:06:32,726
Rose?

78
00:06:36,730 --> 00:06:38,315
(CAT MEOWS)

79
00:06:40,692 --> 00:06:42,819
You know, one day.

80
00:06:45,322 --> 00:06:48,575
Just one day, maybe, I'm going
to meet somebody who gets the whole

81
00:06:48,658 --> 00:06:50,493
"don't wander off" thing.

82
00:06:51,369 --> 00:06:55,373
900 years of phone box travel,
it's the only thing left to surprise me.

83
00:06:55,498 --> 00:06:57,584
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

84
00:07:10,347 --> 00:07:12,057
How can you be ringing?

85
00:07:13,016 --> 00:07:14,851
What's that about ringing?

86
00:07:15,518 --> 00:07:17,729
What am I supposed to do
with a ringing phone?

87
00:07:17,854 --> 00:07:21,024
Don't answer it.
It's not for you.

88
00:07:25,904 --> 00:07:30,200
-And how do you know that?
-'Cause I do. And I'm telling you.

89
00:07:31,409 --> 00:07:33,036
Don't answer it.

90
00:07:33,119 --> 00:07:36,873
Well, if you know so much,
tell me this, how can it be ringing?

91
00:07:37,916 --> 00:07:41,378
It's not even a real phone,
it's not connected, it's not...

92
00:07:44,381 --> 00:07:46,758
(TELEPHONE CONTINUES RINGING)

93
00:07:54,099 --> 00:07:55,308
Hello?

94
00:07:58,311 --> 00:08:00,230
This is the Doctor speaking.

95
00:08:01,648 --> 00:08:04,317
-How may I help you?
-CHILD: Mummy?

96
00:08:06,403 --> 00:08:07,654
Mummy?

97
00:08:08,154 --> 00:08:10,448
Who is this? Who's speaking?

98
00:08:11,324 --> 00:08:13,159
Are you my mummy?

99
00:08:13,243 --> 00:08:15,120
-Who is this?
-Mummy.

100
00:08:17,831 --> 00:08:21,501
How did you ring it?
This isn't a real phone, it's not wired up to...

101
00:08:21,584 --> 00:08:22,836
Mummy?

102
00:08:30,677 --> 00:08:31,928
Rose?

103
00:08:33,096 --> 00:08:34,806
Rose, are you in there?

104
00:08:34,973 --> 00:08:36,599
(CRASHING)

105
00:08:46,776 --> 00:08:51,072
MRS LLOYD: The planes are coming,
can't you hear them? Into the shelter.

106
00:08:51,156 --> 00:08:53,825
None of your nonsense, now move it.

107
00:08:54,701 --> 00:08:58,121
Come on.
Hurry up, get in there. Come on.

108
00:08:58,955 --> 00:09:01,791
Arthur, will you hurry up?

109
00:09:01,875 --> 00:09:03,460
Didn't you hear the siren?

110
00:09:03,543 --> 00:09:07,047
Middle of dinner, every night.
Blooming Germans, don't they eat?

111
00:09:07,130 --> 00:09:08,840
MRS LLOYD: I can hear the planes.

112
00:09:08,965 --> 00:09:10,300
Don't you eat?

113
00:09:10,467 --> 00:09:13,344
Keep your voice down, will you?
It's an air raid.

114
00:09:16,139 --> 00:09:18,016
Get in, look, there's a war on.

115
00:09:18,141 --> 00:09:20,685
I know there's a war on,
don't push me.

116
00:10:16,741 --> 00:10:20,078
Get those lights out, please.
Everyone down to the shelter.

117
00:10:20,161 --> 00:10:23,373
Jack? You going down to the shelter?

118
00:10:23,706 --> 00:10:26,876
Only I've got to go off
on some damn silly guard duty.

119
00:10:27,460 --> 00:10:31,548
Barrage balloon? Must've come loose.
Happens now and then.

120
00:10:32,465 --> 00:10:35,426
Don't you RAF boys use them
for target practice?

121
00:10:37,971 --> 00:10:39,722
Excellent bottom.

122
00:10:41,766 --> 00:10:44,727
I say, old man,
there's a time and a place.

123
00:10:45,145 --> 00:10:47,230
Look, you should really be off.

124
00:10:49,774 --> 00:10:51,109
Sorry, old man.

125
00:10:52,443 --> 00:10:56,406
I've got to go meet a girl.
But you've got an excellent bottom, too.

126
00:11:44,287 --> 00:11:46,789
(BOMBS DROPPING OUTSIDE)

127
00:11:50,335 --> 00:11:52,962
-Many kids out there?
-Yes, miss.

128
00:11:54,130 --> 00:11:57,467
Still carving. Sit and wait.

129
00:11:58,843 --> 00:12:00,178
Got the whole air raid.

130
00:12:00,303 --> 00:12:04,182
-Look. Bet it's off the black market.
-That's enough.

131
00:12:17,570 --> 00:12:19,489
(SCREAMING IN TERROR)

132
00:12:24,327 --> 00:12:27,664
-JACK: Okay, I got you.
-Who's got me?

133
00:12:28,539 --> 00:12:30,833
Who's got me and how?

134
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:33,253
I'm just programming
your descent pattern.

135
00:12:33,336 --> 00:12:37,507
Stay as still as you can and keep
your hands and feet inside the light field.

136
00:12:37,590 --> 00:12:38,675
Descent pattern?

137
00:12:38,758 --> 00:12:41,261
And can you switch off your cell phone?

138
00:12:42,095 --> 00:12:45,014
No, seriously,
it interferes with my instruments.

139
00:12:46,099 --> 00:12:48,017
No one ever believes that.

140
00:12:49,936 --> 00:12:51,980
Thank you, that's much better.

141
00:12:52,063 --> 00:12:54,065
Yeah, that's a real load off, that is.

142
00:12:54,190 --> 00:12:56,818
I'm hanging in the sky
in the middle of a German air raid

143
00:12:56,901 --> 00:13:00,530
with a Union Jack across my chest but,
hey, my mobile phone's off.

144
00:13:00,613 --> 00:13:02,407
Be with you in a moment.

145
00:13:03,950 --> 00:13:08,746
COMPUTER: The mobile device indicates
non-contemporaneous life-form.

146
00:13:08,871 --> 00:13:10,581
She's not from round here, no.

147
00:13:10,707 --> 00:13:12,875
Ready for you. Hold tight.

148
00:13:12,959 --> 00:13:15,295
-To what?
-Fair point.

149
00:13:16,087 --> 00:13:18,047
(SCREAMING)

150
00:13:25,221 --> 00:13:28,433
I got you. You're fine,
you're just fine.

151
00:13:28,641 --> 00:13:32,061
The tractor beam,
it can scramble your head just a little.

152
00:13:35,231 --> 00:13:36,899
-Hello.
-Hello.

153
00:13:38,401 --> 00:13:39,610
Hello.

154
00:13:41,571 --> 00:13:46,159
Sorry. There was "hello" twice there.
Dull but, you know, thorough.

155
00:13:46,576 --> 00:13:48,578
-Are you all right?
-Fine.

156
00:13:51,247 --> 00:13:53,416
Why, you expecting me
to faint or something?

157
00:13:53,499 --> 00:13:54,834
You look a little dizzy.

158
00:13:54,917 --> 00:13:57,628
What about you?
You're not even in focus.

159
00:14:28,284 --> 00:14:31,746
It's got to be black market.
You couldn't get all this on coupons.

160
00:14:31,829 --> 00:14:35,124
Ernie, how many times?
We are guests in this house.

161
00:14:35,208 --> 00:14:38,169
We will not make comments of that kind.
Washing up.

162
00:14:38,544 --> 00:14:40,004
Oh, Nancy.

163
00:14:40,463 --> 00:14:43,716
-Haven't seen you at one of these before.
-He told me about it.

164
00:14:43,800 --> 00:14:45,968
-Sleeping rough?
-Yes, miss.

165
00:14:46,511 --> 00:14:49,138
All right, then.

166
00:14:49,222 --> 00:14:52,850
One slice each. And I want to see
everybody chewing properly.

167
00:14:52,975 --> 00:14:55,561
-Thank you, miss.
-Thanks, miss.

168
00:14:57,688 --> 00:14:59,190
Thank you, miss.

169
00:15:00,691 --> 00:15:02,568
DOCTOR: Thanks, miss.

170
00:15:03,903 --> 00:15:06,572
It's all right.
Everybody stay where they are.

171
00:15:06,656 --> 00:15:08,741
Good here, isn't it?
Who's got the salt?

172
00:15:08,825 --> 00:15:11,994
Back in your seats.
He shouldn't be here either.

173
00:15:15,706 --> 00:15:19,836
-So, you lot, what's the story?
-What do you mean?

174
00:15:19,919 --> 00:15:23,881
-You're homeless, right? Living rough?
-Why do you want to know that?

175
00:15:24,173 --> 00:15:25,341
You a copper?

176
00:15:25,425 --> 00:15:28,594
I'm not a copper. What's a copper
going to do with you lot anyway?

177
00:15:28,678 --> 00:15:30,430
Arrest you for starving?

178
00:15:32,682 --> 00:15:35,184
I make it 1941.
You lot shouldn't even be in London.

179
00:15:35,268 --> 00:15:37,437
Should've been evacuated
to the country by now.

180
00:15:37,520 --> 00:15:40,148
I was evacuated.
Sent me to a farm.

181
00:15:40,231 --> 00:15:42,483
-So why'd you come back?
-There was a man there.

182
00:15:42,567 --> 00:15:44,777
Yeah. Same with Ernie.
Two homes ago.

183
00:15:44,861 --> 00:15:48,364
Shut up. It's better on the streets anyway.
It's better food.

184
00:15:48,448 --> 00:15:51,075
JIM: Yeah. Nancy always gets
the best food for us.

185
00:15:51,200 --> 00:15:53,661
-So that's what you do, is it, Nancy?
-What is?

186
00:15:53,744 --> 00:15:57,623
Soon as the sirens go, you find a big,
fat family meal, still warm on the table,

187
00:15:57,707 --> 00:16:00,293
with everyone down
in the air raid shelter and bingo.

188
00:16:00,376 --> 00:16:02,795
Feeding frenzy for the homeless kids
of London town.

189
00:16:02,879 --> 00:16:05,423
Puddings for all, as long as
the bombs don't get you.

190
00:16:05,548 --> 00:16:07,842
-Something wrong with that?
-Wrong? It's brilliant.

191
00:16:07,925 --> 00:16:11,471
I'm not sure if it's Marxism in action
or a West End musical.

192
00:16:12,930 --> 00:16:16,142
Why'd you follow me?
What do you want?

193
00:16:16,267 --> 00:16:19,395
I want to know how a phone
that isn't a phone gets a phone call.

194
00:16:19,479 --> 00:16:22,315
-You seem to be the one to ask.
-I did you a favour.

195
00:16:22,398 --> 00:16:25,026
I told you not to answer it.
That's all I'm telling you.

196
00:16:25,109 --> 00:16:28,070
Great, thanks.
And I want to find a blonde in a Union Jack.

197
00:16:28,154 --> 00:16:32,325
I mean, a specific one, I didn't just
wake up this morning with a craving.

198
00:16:32,742 --> 00:16:34,785
Anybody seen a girl like that?

199
00:16:35,828 --> 00:16:38,581
-What have I done wrong?
-You took two slices.

200
00:16:38,998 --> 00:16:41,167
No blondes, no flags.

201
00:16:41,292 --> 00:16:42,877
Anything else before you leave?

202
00:16:42,960 --> 00:16:45,171
There is, actually.
Thanks for asking.

203
00:16:45,254 --> 00:16:46,547
Something I've been looking for.

204
00:16:46,631 --> 00:16:49,383
Would've fallen from the sky
a month ago, but not a bomb.

205
00:16:49,467 --> 00:16:51,886
Not the usual kind anyway.
Wouldn't have exploded.

206
00:16:51,969 --> 00:16:54,639
Probably would've buried itself
in the ground somewhere.

207
00:16:54,764 --> 00:16:58,684
And it would've looked
something like this.

208
00:17:01,604 --> 00:17:02,647
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

209
00:17:02,772 --> 00:17:05,650
Mummy?
Are you in there, Mummy?

210
00:17:07,985 --> 00:17:09,195
Mummy.

211
00:17:10,279 --> 00:17:12,365
-Who was the last one in?
-Him.

212
00:17:12,490 --> 00:17:14,742
He came round the back.
Who came in the front?

213
00:17:14,825 --> 00:17:16,953
-Me.
-Did you close the door?

214
00:17:17,119 --> 00:17:19,205
Did you close the door?

215
00:17:19,455 --> 00:17:21,791
Mummy. Mummy.

216
00:17:22,792 --> 00:17:25,127
Mummy.

217
00:17:30,800 --> 00:17:32,718
What's this, then?

218
00:17:32,843 --> 00:17:35,930
Never easy being the only
child left out in the cold, you know.

219
00:17:36,013 --> 00:17:38,975
-I suppose you'd know.
-I do, actually, yes.

220
00:17:39,809 --> 00:17:41,644
It's not exactly a child.

221
00:17:42,311 --> 00:17:44,814
Mummy.

222
00:17:45,314 --> 00:17:48,067
Everybody out.
Across the back garden, under the fence.

223
00:17:48,150 --> 00:17:49,610
Now. Go. Move.

224
00:17:54,156 --> 00:17:58,327
Come on, baby, we've got to go.
It's just like a game, just like chasing.

225
00:17:58,452 --> 00:18:00,121
Take your coat. Go on.

226
00:18:01,163 --> 00:18:02,498
Go.

227
00:18:02,623 --> 00:18:04,834
Mummy. Mummy.

228
00:18:04,959 --> 00:18:07,003
Please let me in, Mummy.

229
00:18:08,588 --> 00:18:10,423
Please let me in, Mummy.

230
00:18:10,506 --> 00:18:11,841
You all right?

231
00:18:11,966 --> 00:18:13,593
Please let me in.

232
00:18:14,802 --> 00:18:16,512
You mustn't let him touch you.

233
00:18:16,596 --> 00:18:17,847
What happens if he touches me?

234
00:18:17,930 --> 00:18:20,182
-He makes you like him.
-And what's he like?

235
00:18:20,266 --> 00:18:22,685
-I've got to go.
-Nancy, what's he like?

236
00:18:25,688 --> 00:18:27,106
He's empty.

237
00:18:27,189 --> 00:18:29,317
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

238
00:18:29,442 --> 00:18:31,360
It's him.

239
00:18:31,444 --> 00:18:35,781
He can make phones ring.
He can. Just like with that police box you saw.

240
00:18:42,371 --> 00:18:44,832
Are you my mummy?

241
00:18:44,999 --> 00:18:46,709
(LIVELY MUSIC PLAYING)

242
00:18:46,792 --> 00:18:48,127
Mummy?

243
00:18:49,003 --> 00:18:50,546
Mummy?

244
00:18:51,297 --> 00:18:53,382
Please let me in, Mummy.

245
00:18:54,216 --> 00:18:58,220
Mummy. Mummy. Mummy.

246
00:18:59,388 --> 00:19:01,349
You stay here if you want to.

247
00:19:01,474 --> 00:19:03,225
Mummy. Mummy. Mummy...

248
00:19:03,351 --> 00:19:05,561
Mummy.

249
00:19:05,853 --> 00:19:08,356
Let me in, please, Mummy.

250
00:19:09,398 --> 00:19:12,401
-Please let me in.
-Your mummy isn't here.

251
00:19:14,862 --> 00:19:17,198
-Are you my mummy?
-No mummies here.

252
00:19:17,823 --> 00:19:19,742
Nobody here but us chickens.

253
00:19:20,910 --> 00:19:22,662
Well. This chicken.

254
00:19:22,745 --> 00:19:24,246
I'm scared.

255
00:19:26,666 --> 00:19:29,168
Why are those other children
frightened of you?

256
00:19:29,251 --> 00:19:32,588
Please let me in, Mummy.
I'm scared of the bombs.

257
00:19:36,092 --> 00:19:39,220
Okay. I'm opening the door now.

258
00:20:10,960 --> 00:20:13,796
-JACK: Better now?
-You got lights in here?

259
00:20:17,550 --> 00:20:19,135
-Hello.
-Hello.

260
00:20:19,468 --> 00:20:20,553
Hello.

261
00:20:20,636 --> 00:20:23,931
-Let's not start that again.
-Okay.

262
00:20:27,977 --> 00:20:30,604
So, who are you supposed be, then?

263
00:20:30,771 --> 00:20:35,234
Captain Jack Harkness,
133 Squadron, Royal Air Force.

264
00:20:35,568 --> 00:20:37,236
American volunteer.

265
00:20:38,404 --> 00:20:40,906
Liar. This is psychic paper.

266
00:20:40,990 --> 00:20:42,992
It tells me whatever
you want it to tell me.

267
00:20:43,117 --> 00:20:44,493
-How do you know?
-Two things.

268
00:20:44,577 --> 00:20:47,663
One, I have a friend
that uses this all the time

269
00:20:47,747 --> 00:20:52,251
and two, you just handed me
a piece of paper telling me you're single

270
00:20:52,334 --> 00:20:53,669
and you work out.

271
00:20:53,794 --> 00:20:55,588
-Tricky thing, psychic paper.
-Yeah.

272
00:20:55,671 --> 00:20:58,841
Can't let your mind wander
when you're handing it over.

273
00:20:59,133 --> 00:21:02,928
You sort of have a boyfriend
called Mickey Smith

274
00:21:03,012 --> 00:21:06,265
but you consider yourself
to be footloose and fancy free.

275
00:21:06,348 --> 00:21:09,643
-What?
-Actually the word you use is "available”.

276
00:21:09,769 --> 00:21:12,271
-No way.
-And another one, "very".

277
00:21:12,354 --> 00:21:15,191
Shall we try and get along
without the psychic paper?

278
00:21:15,316 --> 00:21:17,526
That would be better, wouldn't it?

279
00:21:19,612 --> 00:21:22,323
-Nice spaceship.
-Gets me around.

280
00:21:23,157 --> 00:21:26,452
Very...Spock.

281
00:21:27,369 --> 00:21:28,537
Who?

282
00:21:28,662 --> 00:21:31,040
Guessing you're not a local boy, then?

283
00:21:32,333 --> 00:21:36,378
A cell phone, a liquid crystal watch
and fabrics that won't be around

284
00:21:36,462 --> 00:21:38,464
for at least another two decades.

285
00:21:38,547 --> 00:21:41,550
-Guessing you're not a local girl.
-Guessing right.

286
00:21:44,345 --> 00:21:46,639
-Burn your hands on the rope?
-Yeah.

287
00:21:47,515 --> 00:21:50,309
We're parked in midair.
Can't anyone down there see us?

288
00:21:50,392 --> 00:21:53,687
No. Can I have a look at your hands
for a moment?

289
00:21:54,313 --> 00:21:56,023
-Why?
-Please.

290
00:22:03,864 --> 00:22:07,409
You can stop acting now.
I know exactly who you are.

291
00:22:08,244 --> 00:22:12,039
-I can spot a Time Agent a mile away.
-A Time Agent?

292
00:22:12,665 --> 00:22:15,417
I've been expecting
one of you guys to show up.

293
00:22:15,584 --> 00:22:17,920
Though not, I must to say,
by barrage balloon.

294
00:22:18,045 --> 00:22:19,672
Do you often travel that way?

295
00:22:19,755 --> 00:22:22,216
Sometimes I get
swept off my feet.

296
00:22:23,592 --> 00:22:25,177
By balloons.

297
00:22:26,595 --> 00:22:29,056
-What are you doing?
-Try to keep still.

298
00:22:32,518 --> 00:22:34,395
(DEVICE BEEPING)

299
00:22:35,229 --> 00:22:40,067
Nanogenes, subatomic robots.
The air in here is full of them.

300
00:22:42,945 --> 00:22:45,614
They just repaired
three layers of your skin.

301
00:22:47,575 --> 00:22:48,951
Tell them thanks.

302
00:22:50,035 --> 00:22:52,621
-Shall we get down to business?
-Business?

303
00:22:53,455 --> 00:22:55,791
Shall we have a drink on the balcony?

304
00:22:58,252 --> 00:22:59,879
Bring up the glasses.

305
00:23:12,600 --> 00:23:14,768
I know I'm standing on something.

306
00:23:24,820 --> 00:23:28,991
-Okay. You have an invisible spaceship.
-Yeah.

307
00:23:30,659 --> 00:23:33,495
Tethered up to Big Ben for some reason.

308
00:23:33,829 --> 00:23:37,791
First rule of active camouflage.
Park somewhere you'll remember.

309
00:24:28,842 --> 00:24:30,302
How'd you follow me here?

310
00:24:30,386 --> 00:24:32,888
I'm good at following, me.
I've got the nose for it.

311
00:24:33,013 --> 00:24:35,474
People can't usually follow me
if I don't want them to.

312
00:24:35,557 --> 00:24:39,061
-My nose has special powers.
-Yeah? Is that why it's so...

313
00:24:39,353 --> 00:24:40,896
-What?
-Nothing.

314
00:24:41,146 --> 00:24:42,731
-What?
-Nothing.

315
00:24:43,899 --> 00:24:46,986
-Your ears have special powers, too?
-What are you trying to say?

316
00:24:47,069 --> 00:24:48,570
Good night, mister.

317
00:24:49,071 --> 00:24:50,239
Nancy.

318
00:24:50,906 --> 00:24:53,158
There's something chasing you
and the other kids.

319
00:24:53,242 --> 00:24:54,994
It looks like a boy
and it isn't a boy.

320
00:24:55,077 --> 00:24:57,579
And it started about a month ago. Right?

321
00:24:59,164 --> 00:25:01,000
The thing I'm looking for.

322
00:25:01,083 --> 00:25:04,086
The thing that fell from the sky.
That's when it landed.

323
00:25:04,211 --> 00:25:06,171
You know what I'm talking about,
don't you?

324
00:25:06,255 --> 00:25:09,341
There was a bomb.
A bomb that wasn't a bomb.

325
00:25:09,758 --> 00:25:11,927
Fell the other end
of Limehouse Green Station.

326
00:25:12,052 --> 00:25:16,056
-Take me there.
-No. Soldiers guarding it. Barbed wire.

327
00:25:16,598 --> 00:25:18,684
-You'd never get through.
-Try me.

328
00:25:18,767 --> 00:25:21,103
You sure you want to know
what's going on in there?

329
00:25:21,186 --> 00:25:22,771
I really want to know.

330
00:25:23,564 --> 00:25:26,025
Then there's someone
you need to talk to first.

331
00:25:26,108 --> 00:25:28,902
-And who might that be?
-The Doctor.

332
00:25:33,282 --> 00:25:36,285
It's getting a bit late.
I should really be getting back.

333
00:25:36,368 --> 00:25:37,953
We're discussing business.

334
00:25:38,037 --> 00:25:41,206
This isn't business,
this is champagne.

335
00:25:41,957 --> 00:25:44,877
I try never to discuss business
with a clear head.

336
00:25:45,044 --> 00:25:47,880
(BOMBS EXPLODING)

337
00:25:47,963 --> 00:25:49,798
Are you traveling alone?

338
00:25:50,799 --> 00:25:54,803
-Are you authorised to negotiate?
-What would we be negotiating?

339
00:25:56,305 --> 00:25:59,808
I have something for the Time Agency.
Something they'd like to buy.

340
00:25:59,933 --> 00:26:02,144
Are you empowered
to make payment?

341
00:26:02,811 --> 00:26:06,398
Well, I should talk to my companion.

342
00:26:06,482 --> 00:26:09,318
-Your companion?
-I should really be getting back to him.

343
00:26:09,401 --> 00:26:11,612
-Him?
-Do you have the time?

344
00:26:15,407 --> 00:26:17,284
(BIG BEN TOLLING)

345
00:26:18,494 --> 00:26:20,120
Okay. That was flash.

346
00:26:21,663 --> 00:26:23,248
That was on the flash side.

347
00:26:23,332 --> 00:26:27,628
So, when you say
your companion...

348
00:26:27,753 --> 00:26:29,671
just how disappointed should I be?

349
00:26:29,797 --> 00:26:32,341
- Okay, we're standing in midair...
-Uh-huh.

350
00:26:32,466 --> 00:26:36,595
...on a spaceship,
during a German air raid.

351
00:26:37,638 --> 00:26:41,016
Do you really think now's a good time
to be coming on to me?

352
00:26:42,684 --> 00:26:43,852
Perhaps not.

353
00:26:44,478 --> 00:26:46,438
It was just a suggestion.

354
00:26:46,855 --> 00:26:48,690
Do you like Glenn Miller?

355
00:26:50,359 --> 00:26:52,694
(MOONLIGHT SERENADE PLAYING)

356
00:26:59,868 --> 00:27:03,664
It's 1941. The height of the London Blitz.

357
00:27:04,540 --> 00:27:06,375
The height of
the German bombing campaign.

358
00:27:06,500 --> 00:27:09,002
And something else
has fallen on London.

359
00:27:09,711 --> 00:27:11,964
A fully equipped Chula warship.

360
00:27:12,798 --> 00:27:16,218
The last one in existence
armed to the teeth.

361
00:27:18,137 --> 00:27:21,473
And I know where it is
because I parked it.

362
00:27:24,393 --> 00:27:28,814
If the agency can name the right price,
I can get it for you.

363
00:27:29,898 --> 00:27:31,567
But in two hours...

364
00:27:32,818 --> 00:27:36,238
a German bomb is going to fall on it
and destroy it forever.

365
00:27:37,656 --> 00:27:40,159
That's your deadline.
That's the deal.

366
00:27:41,243 --> 00:27:43,412
Now, shall we discuss payment?

367
00:27:43,537 --> 00:27:45,497
-You know what I think?
-What?

368
00:27:46,039 --> 00:27:48,333
I think you were talking just there.

369
00:27:48,876 --> 00:27:53,005
Two hours. The bomb falls.
There'll be nothing left but dust and a crater.

370
00:27:53,172 --> 00:27:54,506
Promises, promises.

371
00:27:54,590 --> 00:27:56,758
Are you listening to any of this?

372
00:27:57,176 --> 00:28:01,013
You used to be a Time Agent,
now you're some kind of freelancer.

373
00:28:01,096 --> 00:28:04,016
It's a little harsh.
I like to think of myself as a criminal.

374
00:28:04,099 --> 00:28:05,559
I'll bet you do.

375
00:28:07,102 --> 00:28:10,355
So this companion of yours,
does he handle the business?

376
00:28:10,898 --> 00:28:13,692
Well, I delegate a lot of that, yeah.

377
00:28:13,775 --> 00:28:15,777
Maybe we should go find him.

378
00:28:16,361 --> 00:28:20,616
-And how you going to do that?
-Easy, I'll do a scan for alien tech.

379
00:28:24,203 --> 00:28:26,205
Finally a professional.

380
00:28:37,466 --> 00:28:41,637
NANCY: The bomb's under the tarpaulin.
They put the fence up overnight.

381
00:28:41,929 --> 00:28:44,389
See that building?
The hospital?

382
00:28:46,725 --> 00:28:49,770
-What about it?
-That's where the Doctor is.

383
00:28:54,233 --> 00:28:55,817
You should talk to him.

384
00:28:55,901 --> 00:28:58,403
For now,
I'm more interested in getting in there.

385
00:28:58,487 --> 00:29:01,240
-Talk to the Doctor first.
-Why?

386
00:29:01,615 --> 00:29:04,493
Because then maybe
you won't want to get inside.

387
00:29:07,663 --> 00:29:09,081
Where you going?

388
00:29:10,832 --> 00:29:14,461
There was a lot of food in that house.
I've got mouths to feed.

389
00:29:14,586 --> 00:29:16,421
Should be safe enough now.

390
00:29:16,922 --> 00:29:18,674
Can I ask you a question?

391
00:29:19,591 --> 00:29:22,511
-Who did you lose?
-What?

392
00:29:25,514 --> 00:29:30,102
The way you look after all those kids.
It's 'cause you lost somebody, isn't it?

393
00:29:31,311 --> 00:29:33,814
You're doing all this to make up for it.

394
00:29:36,191 --> 00:29:38,860
My little brother. Jamie.

395
00:29:41,196 --> 00:29:45,033
One night I went out looking for food.
Same night that thing fell.

396
00:29:45,617 --> 00:29:49,621
Told him not to follow me.
I told him it was dangerous. But he just...

397
00:29:50,956 --> 00:29:53,292
He just didn't like being on his own.

398
00:29:53,375 --> 00:29:54,710
What happened?

399
00:29:55,210 --> 00:29:59,047
In the middle of an air raid?
What do you think happened?

400
00:30:04,303 --> 00:30:06,054
-Amazing.
-What is?

401
00:30:06,847 --> 00:30:11,893
1941. Right now, not very far from here

402
00:30:12,019 --> 00:30:15,063
the German war machine
is rolling up the map of Europe.

403
00:30:15,188 --> 00:30:19,401
Country after country, falling like dominoes.
Nothing can stop it, nothing.

404
00:30:20,652 --> 00:30:24,031
Until one tiny, damp,
little island says "no".

405
00:30:25,324 --> 00:30:27,743
No, not here.

406
00:30:30,746 --> 00:30:32,581
A mouse in front of a lion.

407
00:30:35,167 --> 00:30:37,711
You're amazing.
The lot of you.

408
00:30:37,836 --> 00:30:41,757
Don't know what you do to Hitler,
but you frighten the hell out of me.

409
00:30:43,258 --> 00:30:47,721
Off you go, then. Do what you got to do.
Save the world.

410
00:30:55,103 --> 00:30:57,606
(EERIE INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC)

411
00:32:41,209 --> 00:32:45,172
You'll find them everywhere.
In every bed, in every ward.

412
00:32:45,547 --> 00:32:46,715
Hundreds of them.

413
00:32:46,840 --> 00:32:50,135
Yes, I saw.
Why are they still wearing gas masks?

414
00:32:50,218 --> 00:32:52,721
-They're not. Who are you?
-I'm...

415
00:32:53,180 --> 00:32:57,142
-Are you the Doctor?
-Dr Constantine. And you are?

416
00:32:57,809 --> 00:32:59,811
-Nancy sent me.
-Nancy?

417
00:33:00,896 --> 00:33:03,482
That means you must have been
asking about the bomb.

418
00:33:03,565 --> 00:33:04,733
Yes.

419
00:33:06,067 --> 00:33:07,819
What do you know about it?

420
00:33:07,903 --> 00:33:10,572
Nothing. Why I was asking.
What do you know?

421
00:33:11,656 --> 00:33:13,533
Only what it's done.

422
00:33:13,658 --> 00:33:15,827
These people were all caught up
in the blast?

423
00:33:15,911 --> 00:33:17,370
None of them were.

424
00:33:18,914 --> 00:33:20,832
(COUGHING)

425
00:33:25,086 --> 00:33:26,505
You're very sick.

426
00:33:27,088 --> 00:33:30,425
Dying, I should think.
I just haven't been able to find the time.

427
00:33:30,550 --> 00:33:33,386
-Are you a doctor?
-I have my moments.

428
00:33:33,678 --> 00:33:36,097
-Have you examined any of them yet?
-No.

429
00:33:37,098 --> 00:33:39,100
Don't touch the flesh.

430
00:33:39,351 --> 00:33:41,186
-Which one?
-Any one.

431
00:33:48,193 --> 00:33:49,444
Conclusions?

432
00:33:49,569 --> 00:33:52,030
Massive head trauma,
mostly to the left side.

433
00:33:52,113 --> 00:33:54,950
Partial collapse of the chest cavity,
mostly to the right.

434
00:33:55,075 --> 00:33:56,952
There's scarring on
the back of the hand

435
00:33:57,077 --> 00:34:00,455
and the gas mask seems to be
fused to the flesh, but I can't see any burns.

436
00:34:00,539 --> 00:34:02,040
Examine another one.

437
00:34:14,386 --> 00:34:16,972
-This is impossible.
-Examine another.

438
00:34:21,101 --> 00:34:22,894
-This is impossible.
-No.

439
00:34:22,978 --> 00:34:25,814
-They've all got the same injuries.
-Yes.

440
00:34:25,939 --> 00:34:27,899
-Exactly the same.
-Yes.

441
00:34:27,983 --> 00:34:31,987
Identical, all of them, right down to the scar
on the back of the hand.

442
00:34:32,237 --> 00:34:34,406
How did this happen?
How did it start?

443
00:34:34,489 --> 00:34:36,908
When that bomb dropped,
there was just one victim.

444
00:34:36,992 --> 00:34:39,661
-Dead?
-At first.

445
00:34:39,786 --> 00:34:42,289
His injuries were truly dreadful.

446
00:34:42,414 --> 00:34:46,751
By the following morning every doctor
and nurse who had treated him,

447
00:34:46,835 --> 00:34:51,423
who had touched him,
had those exact same injuries.

448
00:34:51,506 --> 00:34:56,595
By the next morning, every patient
on the same ward, the exact same injuries.

449
00:34:56,678 --> 00:34:59,264
Within a week,
the entire hospital.

450
00:35:00,181 --> 00:35:04,019
Physical injuries as plague.

451
00:35:04,853 --> 00:35:06,688
Can you explain that?

452
00:35:08,315 --> 00:35:11,693
What would you say
was the cause of death?

453
00:35:12,110 --> 00:35:13,361
-The head trauma.
-No.

454
00:35:13,486 --> 00:35:15,196
-Asphyxiation?
-No.

455
00:35:15,447 --> 00:35:17,866
-The collapse of the chest cavity.
-No.

456
00:35:17,991 --> 00:35:20,452
All right,
what was the cause of death?

457
00:35:22,037 --> 00:35:23,496
There wasn't one.

458
00:35:24,497 --> 00:35:26,333
They're not dead.

459
00:35:33,006 --> 00:35:35,467
It's all right,
they are harmless.

460
00:35:35,550 --> 00:35:38,887
They just sort of sit there.

461
00:35:39,346 --> 00:35:42,390
No heartbeat.
No life signs of any kind.

462
00:35:43,016 --> 00:35:46,394
They just don't die.

463
00:35:46,645 --> 00:35:49,898
And they've just been left here.
Nobody's doing anything?

464
00:35:50,023 --> 00:35:52,901
I try and make them comfortable.
What else is there?

465
00:35:52,984 --> 00:35:54,819
Just you?
You're the only one here.

466
00:35:54,903 --> 00:35:58,657
Before this war began
I was a father and a grandfather.

467
00:35:58,865 --> 00:36:02,243
Now I'm neither.
But I'm still a doctor.

468
00:36:02,869 --> 00:36:05,580
Yeah. I know the feeling.

469
00:36:05,705 --> 00:36:10,085
I suspect the plan is to blow up the hospital
and blame it on a German bomb.

470
00:36:10,210 --> 00:36:12,420
-Probably too late.
-I know.

471
00:36:12,504 --> 00:36:14,839
There are isolated cases.

472
00:36:17,842 --> 00:36:21,262
Isolated cases breaking out
all over London.

473
00:36:21,429 --> 00:36:22,764
Stay back.

474
00:36:23,848 --> 00:36:25,016
(COUGHING)

475
00:36:25,100 --> 00:36:29,062
Listen to me. Top floor.

476
00:36:29,270 --> 00:36:31,106
Room 802.

477
00:36:31,189 --> 00:36:34,693
That's where they took the first victim.
The one from the crash site.

478
00:36:34,776 --> 00:36:37,362
-And you must find Nancy again.
-Nancy?

479
00:36:37,445 --> 00:36:38,947
It was her brother.

480
00:36:39,781 --> 00:36:43,868
She knows more than she's saying.
She won't tell me, but she...

481
00:36:49,958 --> 00:36:52,544
Mummy.

482
00:36:55,463 --> 00:36:59,551
Are you my...

483
00:36:59,634 --> 00:37:02,095
mummy?

484
00:37:33,084 --> 00:37:34,961
JACK: Hello?

485
00:37:35,086 --> 00:37:36,171
ROSE: Hello?

486
00:37:36,296 --> 00:37:37,839
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)
JACK: Hello?

487
00:37:41,843 --> 00:37:43,928
Good evening.
Hope we're not interrupting.

488
00:37:44,012 --> 00:37:46,931
Jack Harkness. I've been hearing
all about you on the way over.

489
00:37:47,015 --> 00:37:50,685
He knows, I had to tell him.
About us being Time Agents.

490
00:37:52,270 --> 00:37:55,106
And it's a real pleasure to meet you,
Mr Spock.

491
00:37:57,942 --> 00:37:59,277
Mr Spock?

492
00:37:59,360 --> 00:38:01,780
What was I supposed to say?
You don't have a name.

493
00:38:01,863 --> 00:38:04,199
Don't you ever get tired of "Doctor"?
Doctor who?

494
00:38:04,324 --> 00:38:06,618
Nine centuries in, I'm coping.
Where've you been?

495
00:38:06,701 --> 00:38:09,788
We're in the middle of a London Blitz,
not the time for a stroll.

496
00:38:09,871 --> 00:38:12,373
Who's strolling?
I went by barrage balloon.

497
00:38:12,499 --> 00:38:14,876
-Only way to see an air raid.
-What?

498
00:38:15,001 --> 00:38:17,128
Listen, what's a Chula warship?

499
00:38:18,797 --> 00:38:20,048
Chula?

500
00:38:26,387 --> 00:38:28,973
Please, Mummy.
Please let me in.

501
00:38:29,057 --> 00:38:31,518
I'm scared of the bombs,
Mummy.

502
00:38:31,726 --> 00:38:33,228
Please, Mummy.

503
00:38:36,022 --> 00:38:37,482
Mummy.

504
00:38:38,858 --> 00:38:40,568
Mummy.

505
00:38:57,752 --> 00:39:00,922
This just isn't possible.
How did this happen?

506
00:39:01,172 --> 00:39:03,424
-What kind of Chula ship landed here?
-What?

507
00:39:03,508 --> 00:39:05,009
He said it was a warship.

508
00:39:05,093 --> 00:39:07,262
He stole it,
parked it somewhere out there.

509
00:39:07,345 --> 00:39:10,598
Somewhere a bomb's gonna fall on it.
Unless we make him an offer.

510
00:39:10,682 --> 00:39:13,017
-What kind of warship?
-Does it matter?

511
00:39:13,101 --> 00:39:14,435
It has nothing to do with this.

512
00:39:14,561 --> 00:39:18,106
This started at the bomb site.
It's got everything to do with it.

513
00:39:18,189 --> 00:39:20,441
-What kind of warship?
-An ambulance.

514
00:39:22,527 --> 00:39:26,447
Look. That's what you chased
through the time vortex.

515
00:39:26,906 --> 00:39:31,244
It's space junk, I wanted to kid you
it was valuable, it's empty.

516
00:39:31,536 --> 00:39:33,788
I made sure of it,
nothing but a shell.

517
00:39:33,872 --> 00:39:35,290
I threw it at you.

518
00:39:35,373 --> 00:39:38,543
Saw your time travel vehicle,
love the retro look by the way,

519
00:39:38,626 --> 00:39:41,462
-nice panels, threw you the bait...
-Bait?

520
00:39:41,963 --> 00:39:45,633
I wanted to sell it to you, then destroy it
before you found it was junk.

521
00:39:45,717 --> 00:39:49,095
-You said it was a warship.
-They have ambulances in wars.

522
00:39:52,056 --> 00:39:54,475
It's a con. I was conning you.

523
00:39:54,559 --> 00:39:57,896
That's what I am, I'm a con man.
Thought you were Time Agents.

524
00:39:57,979 --> 00:40:01,065
-You're not, are you?
-Just a couple more freelancers.

525
00:40:01,149 --> 00:40:05,570
Oh! Should've known, the way you guys
are blending in with the local colour.

526
00:40:05,653 --> 00:40:08,489
Flag Girl was bad enough,
but U-boat Captain?

527
00:40:09,574 --> 00:40:14,412
Anyway, whatever's happening here
has got nothing to do with that ship.

528
00:40:14,495 --> 00:40:16,915
What is happening here, Doctor?

529
00:40:18,082 --> 00:40:20,335
Human DNA is being rewritten.

530
00:40:20,835 --> 00:40:23,004
-By an idiot.
-What do you mean?

531
00:40:23,129 --> 00:40:26,925
I don't know, some kind of virus.
Converting humans into these things.

532
00:40:27,008 --> 00:40:29,844
But why? What's the point?

533
00:40:33,181 --> 00:40:34,349
Mummy.

534
00:40:38,186 --> 00:40:39,854
Where's my mummy?

535
00:40:41,189 --> 00:40:42,440
Mummy.

536
00:41:09,550 --> 00:41:11,302
Are you my mummy?

537
00:41:16,808 --> 00:41:18,393
Mummy.

538
00:41:19,143 --> 00:41:20,812
PATIENTS: Mummy.

539
00:41:20,895 --> 00:41:22,814
Mummy.

540
00:41:22,897 --> 00:41:25,525
-What's happening?
-DOCTOR: I don't know.

541
00:41:30,822 --> 00:41:32,073
Mummy.

542
00:41:32,657 --> 00:41:34,742
It's me. Nancy.

543
00:41:36,911 --> 00:41:38,329
Don't let them touch you.

544
00:41:38,413 --> 00:41:41,582
-What happens if they touch us?
-You're looking at it.

545
00:41:43,584 --> 00:41:47,755
-Are you my mummy?
-It's Nancy, your sister.

546
00:41:51,217 --> 00:41:53,928
You're dead, Jamie.
You're dead.

547
00:41:54,095 --> 00:41:56,097
Mummy.

548
00:41:56,597 --> 00:41:59,183
Mummy.

549
00:41:59,267 --> 00:42:01,894
ALL: Mummy. Mummy...

550
00:42:02,854 --> 00:42:05,940
-Mummy.
-Mummy.

551
00:42:06,607 --> 00:42:08,192
Mummy...

552
00:42:52,487 --> 00:42:55,406
I don't know what's happening
but I had nothing to do with it.

553
00:42:55,490 --> 00:42:56,824
I'll tell you what's happening.

554
00:42:56,908 --> 00:42:59,911
You forgot to set your alarm clock.
It's Volcano Day.

555
00:43:00,578 --> 00:43:02,497
That door should hold it for a bit.

556
00:43:02,580 --> 00:43:04,791
The door?
The wall didn't stop it.

557
00:43:05,166 --> 00:43:06,751
Halt. Don't move.

558
00:43:06,834 --> 00:43:08,753
Go on, ask me anything, I'm on fire.

559
00:43:08,836 --> 00:43:11,089
You've got the moves,
show me your moves.

560
00:43:11,172 --> 00:43:13,591
The world doesn't end
"cause the Doctor dances.

561
00:43:13,674 --> 00:43:14,926
Stay back.

562
00:43:16,302 --> 00:43:17,345
Mummy.

563
00:43:18,012 --> 00:43:19,597
-Doctor.
-Secure those gates.

564
00:43:19,680 --> 00:43:21,140
-Why?
-Just do it.

565
00:43:21,265 --> 00:43:24,435
All that weapons tech in the hands
of an hysterical four-year-old

566
00:43:24,519 --> 00:43:25,937
looking for his mummy.

567
00:43:26,020 --> 00:43:28,356
And nothing in
the world can stop it.

